english:
  title: 'Mid-Autumn at Cheonwang Peak: The Moon Unseen'
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I fled the ledgers of office to climb the towering heights,
    Yet Heaven's jealousy seized this auspicious night.
    Mist swells across the world—the eight horizons drowned in sea,
    While wind shakes the stone mountains with ten thousand thunderclaps' decree.

    From Heaven's Pillar I learn that such glorious wandering must end,
    From Jade's clear dream no return can I foresee or comprehend.
    Then briefly the stubborn clouds part, opening a narrow seam—
    But who has the power to gather the moon into their dream?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Cheonwang Peak (天王峯): A sacred mountain peak, symbolizing aspiration and transcendence.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Heaven''s Pillar (天柱) and Jade Terrace (瓊臺): Classical references to celestial realms and the dwelling places of immortals, representing the poet''s yearning for escape from worldly concerns.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The eight horizons (八紘): A poetic expression for the vastness of the known world.'
